</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$16.9B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$2.89B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$1.37</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">27.9%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Kinder Morgan generated <strong>$2.89 billion</strong> in unlevered free cash flow in FY2025. This is operating cash flow ($5.91B) minus capital expenditures ($3.02B). Note that pipeline companies often define "Distributable Cash Flow" differently by excluding expansion capex, but we use strict FCF.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>3% per year</strong> for 5 years. This is a very mature, fee-based pipeline business with long-term contracts. High growth is not expected, but steady, inflation-linked rate escalations provide modest and highly predictable top-line bumps.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2% forever</strong> — roughly mirroring long-term inflation. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate). This captures all value from Year 6 to infinity.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>6%</strong> — our required rate of return for a heavily debt-levered pipeline. With a low beta (0.65), a 10Y Treasury at 4.18%, and roughly 50% debt-to-capital, a 6% WACC reflects the low cost of capital available for infrastructure assets.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (-$62.7B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding (2.22B) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">3%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Kinder Morgan operates massive natural gas and CO2 pipelines under take-or-pay contracts. This model provides extreme stability but little organic growth. Expansion capex is yielding modest returns. 3% represents baseline inflation escalators and minor volume increases across their network.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">6%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Pipeline companies are uniquely structured. Using the CAPM: 10Y Treasury (4.18%) + Beta (0.65) × ERP (5.5%) = Cost of Equity of 7.75%. Blended with their massive debt load at a ~5% after-tax cost of debt, the Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) sits right around 6%. It's low-risk infrastructure.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is ~3%, but fossil fuel infrastructure faces extremely long-term headwinds as the energy transition scales. However, natural gas is the transitional fuel. 2% terminal growth ensures the asset value keeps up with long-term inflation without assuming volume growth forever.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
