  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>Why does our model value KMI at around $6 when it trades at ~$33? Because the market values pipelines differently than standard corporations. Here's what a strict DCF inherently misses.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number is too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The Pipeline Valuation Disconnect:</strong> We use a strict Unlevered Free Cash Flow DCF. However, the market prices KMI based on Dividend Yield and "Distributable Cash Flow" (DCF, a metric that ignores growth capex). Yield investors are willing to pay $33 to secure a 5-6% dividend, ignoring the massive debt load because they assume it will be continually refinanced rather than paid off. A standard DCF often severely undervalues pipeline MLPs and C-Corps for this reason.</li>
    <li><strong>Energy Transition Arbitrage:</strong> While wind and solar expand, natural gas is the required baseload power. AI data centers are creating a surge in electricity demand that only natural gas can currently fulfill quickly, massively increasing the value of existing transmission pipelines.</li>
    <li><strong>Replacement Cost:</strong> Regulatory hurdles make building new interstate pipelines nearly impossible in the US today. This gives KMI's existing assets a monopoly-like moat and immense replacement value that isn't captured in trailing cash flows.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Risk:</strong> With $62B+ in debt, KMI is highly sensitive to interest rates. If rates stay higher for longer, refinancing their massive debt maturities will eat heavily into cash flow and dividends.</li>
    <li><strong>Terminal Decline:</strong> If the energy transition moves faster than expected, natural gas volumes could face a structural decline in the 2030s, meaning terminal growth could be negative, not 2%.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Overreach:</strong> The FERC regulates the rates pipelines can charge. Adverse rulings can cap their returns on capital.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the intrinsic value so much lower than the stock price?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Pipeline companies carry massive amounts of debt ($62.7B for KMI). In a traditional Enterprise Value DCF, you subtract total debt from the Enterprise Value to find Equity Value. Because KMI's debt load is so large compared to its unlevered FCF, the remaining equity value appears very small. The market ignores this and prices KMI strictly on its dividend yield and "Distributable Cash Flow," assuming the debt will just be rolled over forever.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 6% discount rate? Isn't that low?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">6% represents a Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC). KMI has a low beta (0.65) meaning its stock is less volatile than the market, leading to a low Cost of Equity. Furthermore, they are funded with ~50% debt, which is cheaper than equity. Blending these together results in a low hurdle rate, which is typical for regulated infrastructure assets.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>What is Distributable Cash Flow?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Distributable Cash Flow (DCF) is a non-GAAP metric used by pipelines. It starts with net income and adds back depreciation, but subtracts only "sustaining" capital expenditures, completely ignoring money spent on "expansion." By ignoring expansion capex, DCF is much higher than Free Cash Flow, making the dividend look safer than it is on a strict cash basis.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

